[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    131[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section, EHR integration paragraph[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    132[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The recipe mentions EHR integration (HL7 FHIR, ADT feeds) as the "hard part" but doesn't discuss the networking implications. EHR systems are typically on-premises or in a separate VPC. Receiving clinical notes from an EHR requires either AWS PrivateLink, VPN/Direct Connect, or an integration engine in a DMZ. PHI transiting between the EHR and AWS must stay encrypted and within controlled network paths. This is a significant architectural decision that deserves at least a sentence.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    133[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Add a brief note in the EHR integration paragraph: "Network connectivity to your EHR (Direct Connect, Site-to-Site VPN, or PrivateLink) must be established with TLS encryption and restricted security groups. PHI should never traverse the public internet between your EHR and AWS, even encrypted."[K
